<HEADLINE>
<P>
JOSEPHINE JOHNSON; PULITZER PRIZE-WINNING AUTHOR 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Josephine Johnson, 79, who won the Pulitzer Prize for fiction in 1934 for her 
first novel, "Now in November," written when she was 24. 
</P>
<P>
She wrote 11 books, including novels, short stories and poetry. One of her most 
popular books was the 1969 "Inland Island," written in diary format about a 
year spent on her 37-acre property. Critics acclaimed it as a modern version of 
Henry David Thoreau's "Walden." She had been a regular contributor to the 
monthly Ohio Magazine. In Batavia, Ohio, on Feb. 27 of pneumonia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
