<HEADLINE>
<P>
FAKE OIL SPILL TO TEST RESPONSE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In the wake of the Long Beach oil spill, Coast Guard officials have decided to 
stage a 5-hour drill Thursday in San Diego waters to test the local response to 
a similar event. 
</P>
<P>
For the drill, scheduled to begin at 9 a.m. near the entrance to San Diego Bay, 
the Coast Guard will team with the Navy and an industry-supported spill 
clean-up group called Clean Coastal Waters. 
</P>
<P>
The groups will deploy oil containment booms and skimming equipment in response 
to a simulated spill of fuel oil spewing from an imaginary boat grounded near 
the Zuniga jetty. 
</P>
<P>
Officials will evaluate the groups' response, how effectively they communicate 
with one another, and how efficiently they use the equipment. 
</P>
<P>
"We will test the people and the equipment to see how well the response 
community will be able to work in case there were a spill here," said Coast 
Guard Lt. Stephen LaLonde. 
</P>
</TEXT>
