<HEADLINE>
<P>
CONSUMER VIEWS: CONSUMERS; 
</P>
<P>
SETTLING AN ACCIDENT 'ON THE SPOT' 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By DON G. CAMPBELL, Campbell is a syndicated columnist and former Times staff 
writer. 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Question: Something interesting has happened to me, and I am wondering if it 
indicates a new trend in the automobile insurance field. A few days ago, I was 
driving my brand-new, 2-month-old Toyota Celica when a woman driving a van 
broadsided me at an intersection. I had the right of way. 
</P>
<P>
After making sure I wasn't hurt, the woman readily admitted she had stopped for 
the "Stop" sign but had then pulled out and hit me. She was most insistent that 
both of us avoid our insurance companies and said she would write me a check 
with no questions asked as soon as I had an appraisal made. 
</P>
<P>
What really surprised me, though, was that when I checked with my insurance 
company, they seemed to think it was a perfectly logical way to settle the 
matter. When the lady and I talked later, she told me she had checked with her 
insurance carrier and that they, too, approved of the arrangement. The lady 
obviously wants to keep the accident off her record and keep her premiums down. 
In a subsequent phone conversation with her (before I had gotten my estimate), 
she said that when I was satisfied with the estimate, she would meet me at her 
bank, write me a check -- which I could deposit to my own account immediately 
-- and she would have a notarized form releasing her of liability for me to 
sign. The advantage to me, of course, would be that I would get my car repaired 
without paying the deductible. 
</P>
<P>
It all seems perfectly legal, and I have gotten the impression that "let's 
settle this matter privately" is a new trend. Is it? And as the injured party, 
are there any dangers in it for me? -- D.C. 
</P>
<P>
Answer: According to Mary Crystal, director of communications for the Insurance 
Information Institute at Preston, Calif., and Bob Christensen, a longtime State 
Farm Insurance agent in Glendale, this is a long way from being a "new trend." 
It's been going on for many years, and at one time or another, virtually all of 
us have participated in it. (You backed out of a parking space and nicked the 
car pulling in behind you. It was your fault, but it was also a $50 repair job, 
far under the deductible for both of you. So your "victim" had the nick taken 
care of and sent you the bill. End of story.) 
</P>
<P>
"It's always depended on circumstances," Crystal said. "How much money is 
involved, whether one or the other of you is at fault, that sort of thing. 
People today are just more sensitive about premiums and what can affect them, 
and so the dollar figures have gone up." 
</P>
<P>
State Farm's Christensen concurred. "The key to the whole thing," he adds, "is 
injury. If there is no injury, then it's simply a matter of money and the two 
parties can work out an agreeable deal between them. But both of them have to 
be careful when they do this. It sounds to me like the lady who hit this person 
may have a driving problem that could seriously impact her premiums if it 
became a matter of record, since she was clearly at fault. The comment about 
having a (liability release) for him to sign would also seem to suggest that 
she's had a little experience in this sort of thing. State Farm, however, 
wouldn't raise the premium of the driver who wasn't at fault, but simply not 
having to pay the deductible would make a deal like this worthwhile for him." 
</P>
<P>
But, as Christensen points out, both parties to a private settlement such as 
this have to watch out for some potential pitfalls. The victim has to make sure 
there are no physical injuries that might flare up later; that the estimate 
from the body shop is a firm one and that additional repairs won't surface 
after he's accepted her check (because, Christensen said, "once he's accepted 
and banked her check he's got no recourse"), and that the check he receives is 
"good." Also, if the victim's car is going to be out of action for several 
days, the other party should pay for the rental. "The victim shouldn't be out 
of pocket for anything," Christensen added. 
</P>
<P>
For the guilty party (in this case the woman who broadsided the other car), 
"her insistence that he sign a release of liability when payment is made is 
perfectly good business," Christensen stated. "She doesn't want him coming back 
in six months with a mysterious whiplash injury." 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column 
</P>
