<P>
CEAUSESCU'S BODYGUARDS FREED 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Wire Services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
BUCHAREST, Romania 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Nicolae Ceausescu's bodyguards walked free today after they told a military 
court they had simply obeyed orders when they helped the executed Romanian 
dictator in his abortive bid to flee last December's uprising. 
</P>
<P>
The four senior officers of the dreaded secret police rushed the fugitive 
Stalinist leader and his wife, Elena, to the roof of the Communist Party 
headquarters Dec. 22, where they fled in a helicopter to escape crowds baying 
for their blood. 
</P>
<P>
The couple were captured and shot by firing squad Dec. 25 after a military 
trial, which was later shown on television. 
</P>
<P>
The bodyguards were arrested on charges of undermining the economy, destroying 
public property and undermining state power. 
</P>
<P>
But they were acquitted by a military tribunal today after pleading that they 
had only been doing their duty. 
</P>
</TEXT>
