P. M. BRIEFING; 
</P>
<P>
JANUARY HELP-WANTED ADS DROP 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Wire Services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
NEW YORK 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A key index monitoring advertising placed by companies seeking employees was 
down three points in January compared to December, a nationwide survey said 
today. 
</P>
<P>
The Conference Board, a nonprofit research organization, said in a survey that 
its Help-Wanted Advertising Index slipped to 146 in January, down from 149 in 
December. 
</P>
<P>
The monthly indicator, first set at 100 in 1967, is based on the help-wanted 
advertising volume in 51 major newspapers across the United States. 
</P>
<P>
"The January figure reading is up only one point from the November figure, but 
five points below the October figure and substantially lower than the year-ago 
figure of 155," the survey said. 
</P>
<P>
Among regions recording a decline was the Pacific, down to 269 from 290. 
</P>
</TEXT>
