<HEADLINE>
<P>
PEOPLE'S PHARMACY: CHRYSANTHEMUM FLOWERS, FORMIC ACID BATTLE NITS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By JOE GRAEDON and AND TERESA GRAEDON 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Myths die hard. When we were children lice were considered a sign of 
slovenliness. Memories of kerosene shampoos and short haircuts still send 
shivers down parents' spines. 
</P>
<P>
Even these days, most school nurses get a pained expression on their faces at 
the mention of lice. They're on the front line of this epidemic. 
</P>
<P>
Despite effective lice shampoos, ridding a school of these unwanted intruders 
is not always easy, which is why most schools demand that their children's 
scalps be free of nits (tiny white louse eggs) -- before the child can return. 
</P>
<P>
A mother cornered us at a recent gathering and whispered that her daughter had 
been sent home with lice. This woman was incensed that she had been called at 
work and forced to pick her child up in the middle of the day. 
</P>
<P>
She felt humiliated and annoyed that she had to spend several hours after 
treating her daughter with lice shampoo trying to comb the nits out of the 
child's long, curly hair. 
</P>
<P>
Once upon a time the No Nit rule was the only effective way to control lice. 
Over-the-counter shampoos (A-200, R &amp; C and Rid) only kill lice. The eggs, 
which can hatch up to 10 days later, are resistant. Consequently, it was 
essential to comb out the nits to prevent reinfestation. 
</P>
<P>
Today, however, there are prescription products that are highly effective and 
may offer an alternative to nit removal. Ovide (malathion) is capable of 
killing nits as well as lice. And Nix Creme Rinse (permethrin) stays on the 
hair to kill young lice as they emerge from the egg. With one application 97% 
to 99% of children are louse-free after two weeks, even without nit removal. 
</P>
<P>
Nix is easier to use than Ovide and the active ingredient permethrin is a 
derivative of chrysanthemum flowers. The insecticidal properties of this plant 
have been appreciated for centuries. 
</P>
<P>
As effective as the new prescription products may be, schools are unlikely to 
change No Nit policies, as they cannot require all children be treated with an 
expensive prescription. 
</P>
<P>
To make nit removal easier, parents may wish to try a new over-the-counter 
preparation (Step 2 from the GenDerm Corp.). It contains formic acid which 
helps loosen the eggs after lice shampoo treatment. 
</P>
<P>
Despite the stigma associated with lice, anyone can have them. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column 
</P>
